  <exercises>
    <title>Fractions - Sometimes They Cannot be Avoided</title>

    <exercise>
      <title>Explanation and examples</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Sometimes there is no avoiding fractions when applying the method of substitution to a linear system of equations.  For eaxmple, consider the following system of equations.       
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  -5x+3y\amp=4\\
                  6x-7y\amp=2\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
            No matter which variable we isolate, the expression on the other side of the equation will contain fractions.  Fortunately, once we've made the substitution we can clear away the fractions before proceeding to the solution.  Since there are no "good" choices, let's go ahead and solve the first equation for <m>y</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>-5x+3y\amp=4</mrow>
              <mrow>-5x+3y\addright{5x}\amp=4\addright{5x}</mrow>
              <mrow>3y\amp=5x+4</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{3}}3y\amp=\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{3}}(5x+4)</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{5}{3}x+\frac{4}{3}</mrow>
            </md>
            We can substitute <m>\frac{5}{3}x+\frac{4}{3}</m> for <m>y</m> in the second original equation and solve the resultant equation for <m>x</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>6x-7\highlight{y}\amp=2</mrow>
              <mrow>6x-7(\highlight{\frac{5}{3}x+\frac{4}{3}})\amp=2</mrow>
              <mrow>6x-\frac{35}{3}x-\frac{28}{3}\amp=2</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}(6x-\frac{35}{3}x-\frac{28}{3})\amp=\multiplyleft{3}2\,\highlight{\text{ (clearing away the fractions)}}</mrow>
              <mrow>18x-35x-28\amp=6</mrow>
              <mrow>-17x-28\amp=6</mrow>
              <mrow>-17x-28\addright{28}\amp=6\addright{28}</mrow>
              <mrow>-17x\amp=34</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-17x}{-17}\amp=\divideunder{34}{-17}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=-2</mrow>
            </md>
            Let's substitute <m>-2</m> for <m>x</m> in the equation <m>y=\frac{5}{3}x+\frac{4}{3}</m> and solve for <m>y</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{5}{3}(\highlight{-2})+\frac{4}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{-6}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-2</mrow>
            </md>
            Our proposed solution is <m>(-2,-2)</m>.  Let's check in the original system.      
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  -5(\highlight{-2})+3(\highlightr{-2})\amp=4\,?\\
                  6(\highlight{-2})-7(\highlightr{-2})\amp=2\,?\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>      
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  10-6\amp=4\,\checkmark\\
                  -12+14\amp=2\,\checkmark\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
            The solution to the given system of equations is the ordered pair <m>(-2,-2)</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Example: Use the method of substitution to solve the following system of equations.      
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  \frac{5}{2}x-\frac{3}{7}y\amp=\frac{71}{28}\\
                  -\frac{7}{9}x+\frac{2}{3}y\amp=-\frac{43}{18}\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>Solution</p>
          <p>
            Good grief.  Let's start by clearing away the fractions, noting that <m>28</m> is the LCD of the fractions in the first equation and <m>18</m> is the LCD of the fractions in the second equation.     
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  \multiplyleft{28}(\frac{5}{2}x-\frac{3}{7}y)\amp=\multiplyleft{28}\frac{71}{28}\\
                  \multiplyleft{18}(-\frac{7}{9}x+\frac{2}{3}y)\amp=\multiplyleft{18}-\frac{43}{18}\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>     
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  70x-12y\amp=71\\
                  -14x+12y\amp=-43\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
            Consideration of our choices for variable isolation does not bring good cheer.  Let's keep the fractions as reasonable as possible and solve the second equation for <m>y</m>. 
            <md>
              <mrow>-14x+12y\amp=-43</mrow>
              <mrow>-14x+12y\addright{14x}\amp=-43\addright{14x}</mrow>
              <mrow>12y\amp=14x-43</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{12}}12y\amp=\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{12}}(14x-43)</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{7}{6}x-\frac{43}{12}</mrow>
            </md>
            Let's go ahead and substitute <m>\frac{7}{6}x-\frac{43}{12}</m> for <m>y</m> in the equation <m>70x-12y=71</m> and solve the resultant equation for <m>x</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>70x-12\highlight{y}\amp=71</mrow>
              <mrow>70x-12(\highlight{\frac{7}{6}x-\frac{43}{12}})\amp=71</mrow>
              <mrow>70x-14x+43\amp=71</mrow>
              <mrow>56x+43\amp=71</mrow>
              <mrow>56x+43\subtractright{43}\amp=71\subtractright{43}</mrow>
              <mrow>56x\amp=28</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{56x}{56}\amp=\divideunder{28}{56}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            Let's substitute <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> for <m>x</m> in the equation <m>y=\frac{7}{6}x-\frac{43}{12}</m> and solve the resultant equation for <m>y</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{7}{6}(\highlight{\frac{1}{2}})-\frac{43}{12}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{7}{12}-\frac{43}{12}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{36}{12}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-3</mrow>
            </md>
            Our proposed solution is <m>(\frac{1}{2},-3)</m> which is pretty clean, so probably correct.  Never-the-less, we need to check it in the original system.    
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  \frac{5}{2}(\highlight{\frac{1}{2}})-\frac{3}{7}(\highlightr{-3})\amp=\frac{71}{28}\,?\\
                  -\frac{7}{9}(\highlight{\frac{1}{2}})+\frac{2}{3}(\highlightr{-3})\amp=-\frac{43}{18}\,?\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>    
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  \frac{5}{4}+\frac{9}{7}\amp=\frac{71}{28}\,?\\
                  -\frac{7}{18}-2\amp=-\frac{43}{18}\,?\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  \frac{5}{4} \cdot \highlight{\frac{7}{7}}+\frac{9}{7} \cdot \highlight{\frac{4}{4}}\amp=\frac{71}{28}\,?\\
                  -\frac{7}{18}-\frac{2}{1} \cdot \highlight{\frac{18}{18}}\amp=-\frac{43}{18}\,?\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
            <me>
              \left\{
                \begin{aligned}
                  \frac{35}{28}+\frac{36}{28}\amp=\frac{71}{28}\,\checkmark\\
                  -\frac{7}{18}-\frac{36}{18}\amp=-\frac{43}{18}\,\checkmark\\
                \end{aligned}
              \right.
            </me>
            The solution to the given system of equations is the ordered pair <m>(\frac{1}{2},-3)</m>.
          </p>
          <p>Criminy.</p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <title>Practice exercises with detailed solutions</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the substitution method to determine the solution to each of the following systems of linear equations.
            <ol>

              <li>
                <m>
                  \left\{
                    \begin{aligned}
                      x\amp=\frac{2}{5}y-2\\
                      -x+3y\amp=28\\
                    \end{aligned}
                  \right.
                </m>
              </li>

              <li>
                <m>
                  \left\{
                    \begin{aligned}
                      -3x+4y\amp=27\\
                      5x-3y\amp=-34\\
                    \end{aligned}
                  \right.
                </m>
              </li>

              <li>
                <m>
                  \left\{
                    \begin{aligned}
                      \frac{5}{2}x-\frac{4}{3}y\amp=-33\\
                      -\frac{1}{5}x+\frac{2}{3}y\amp=6\\
                    \end{aligned}
                  \right.
                </m>
              </li>

              <li>
                <m>
                  \left\{
                    \begin{aligned}
                      \frac{3}{4}x-\frac{5}{2}y\amp=\frac{7}{4}\\
                      -\frac{1}{3}x+y\amp=-1\\
                    \end{aligned}
                  \right.
                </m>
              </li>

              <li>
                <m>
                  \left\{
                    \begin{aligned}
                      -4x+7y\amp=-13\\
                      6x+14y\amp=9\\
                    \end{aligned}
                  \right.
                </m>
              </li>

            </ol>
            <p>
            </p>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>

            <ol>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Our challenge is to solve the following system of equations.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          x\amp=\frac{2}{5}y-2\\
                          -x+3y\amp=28\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    Since <m>x</m> is already isolated in the first equation, let's go ahead and substitute <m>\frac{2}{5}y-2</m> for <m>x</m> in the second equation.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>-(\substitute{\frac{2}{5}y-2})+3y\amp=28</mrow>
                      <mrow>-\frac{2}{5}y+2+3y\amp=28</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Before going any further, we can clear away the fraction by multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>5</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{5}(-\frac{2}{5}y+2+3y)\amp=\multiplyleft{5}28</mrow>
                      <mrow>-2y+10+15y\amp=140</mrow>
                      <mrow>13y+10\amp=140</mrow>
                      <mrow>13y+10\subtractright{10}\amp=140\subtractright{10}</mrow>
                      <mrow>13y\amp=130</mrow>
                      <mrow>\divideunder{13y}{13}\amp=\divideunder{130}{13}</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=10</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Now that we know that the value of <m>y</m> is <m>10</m>, we can substitute <m>10</m> for <m>y</m> in the equation <m>x=\frac{2}{5}y-2</m> to determine the value of <m>x</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>x\amp=\frac{2}{5} \cdot \substitute{10}-2</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=4-2</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    So the solution to the given system of equations is the ordered pair <m>(2,10)</m>.  The reader should verify the solution in both equations (as the author did on his own).
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    We have the opportunity to solve the following system of equations.  Let's take advantage.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          -3x+4y\amp=27\\
                          5x-3y\amp=-34\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    Regardless of which variable we isolate, there are going to be fractions in the resultant equation.  We'll have one fewer fraction if we isolate <m>x</m> in the first equation, so let's do that.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>-3x+4y\amp=27</mrow>
                      <mrow>-3x+4y\subtractright{4y}\amp=27\subtractright{4y}</mrow>
                      <mrow>-3x\amp=27-4y</mrow>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{3}}(-3x)\amp=\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{3}}(27-4y)</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-9+\frac{4}{3}y</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We can now substitute <m>-9+\frac{4}{3}y</m> for <m>x</m> in the equation <m>5x-3y=-34</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>5(\substitute{-9+\frac{4}{3}y})-3y\amp=-34</mrow>
                      <mrow>-45+\frac{20}{3}y-3y\amp=-34</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Before proceeding any further, let's clear away the fraction by multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>3</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}(-45+\frac{20}{3}y-3y)\amp=\multiplyleft{3}-34</mrow>
                      <mrow>-135+20y-9y\amp=-102</mrow>
                      <mrow>-135+11y\amp=-102</mrow>
                      <mrow>-135+11y\addright{135}\amp=-102\addright{135}</mrow>
                      <mrow>11y\amp=33</mrow>
                      <mrow>\divideunder{11y}{11}\amp=\divideunder{33}{11}</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=3</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Knowing that <m>y=3</m>, let's substitute <m>3</m> for <m>y</m> in the equation <m>x=-9+\frac{4}{3}y</m> to determine the value of <m>x</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-9+\frac{4}{3} \cdot \substitute{3}</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-9+4</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-5</mrow>
                    </md>
                    So the solution to the given system of equations is the ordered pair <m>(-5,3)</m>.  The author has verified the solution, as should the reader.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Time to roll up our sleeves, because we're going to tackle the following system of equations.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          \frac{5}{2}x-\frac{4}{3}y\amp=-33\\
                          -\frac{1}{5}x+\frac{2}{3}y\amp=6\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    Once we get over the shock of all the fractions, let's focus on eliminating them.  The LCD of the fractions in the first equation is <m>6</m> and the LCD of the fractions in the second equations is <m>15</m>, so we can clear the fractions in the first equation by multiplying both sides by <m>6</m> and we can clear the fractions from the second equation by multiplying both sides by <m>15</m>.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          \multiplyleft{6}(\frac{5}{2}x-\frac{4}{3}y)\amp=\multiplyleft{6}-33\\
                          \multiplyleft{15}(-\frac{1}{5}x+\frac{2}{3}y)\amp=\multiplyleft{15}6\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    This results in the following system of equations.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          15x-8y\amp=-198\\
                          -3x+10y\amp=90\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    Regardless of the variable we isolate, the resultant equation will have fractions.  As far as fractions go, thirds are relatively friendly, so let's isolate <m>x</m> in the second equation.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>-3x+10y\amp=90</mrow>
                      <mrow>-3x+10y\subtractright{10y}\amp=90\subtractright{10y}</mrow>
                      <mrow>-3x\amp=90-10y</mrow>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{3}}(-3x)\amp=\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{3}}(90-10y)</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-30+\frac{10}{3}y</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Let's go ahead and substitute <m>-30+\frac{10}{3}y</m> for <m>x</m> in the equation <m>15x-8y=-198</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>15(\substitute{-30+\frac{10}{3}y})-8y\amp=-198</mrow>
                      <mrow>-450+50y-8y\amp=-198</mrow>
                      <mrow>-450+42y\amp=-198</mrow>
                      <mrow>-450+42y\addright{450}\amp=-198\addright{450}</mrow>
                      <mrow>42y\amp=252</mrow>
                      <mrow>\divideunder{42y}{42}\amp=\divideunder{252}{42}</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=6</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Let's now substitute <m>6</m> for <m>y</m> in the equation <m>x=-30+\frac{10}{3}y</m> to determine the value of <m>x</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-30+\frac{10}{3}\multiplyright{6}</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-30+20</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=-10</mrow>.
                    </md>
                    The solution to the given system is the ordered pair <m>(-10,6)</m> which the author is confident the reader will verify.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Grab a cup of coffee, because we're going to solve the following system of equations.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          \frac{3}{4}x-\frac{5}{2}y\amp=\frac{7}{4}\\
                          -\frac{1}{3}x+y\amp=-1\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    Our first instinct might be to clear away all of the fractions, but that's probably not the best option.  While we definitely want to clear the fractions from the first equation, a better option for the second equation is probably to just go ahead and isolate <m>y</m>.  We begin with the second action.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>-\frac{1}{3}x+y\amp=-1</mrow>
                      <mrow>-\frac{1}{3}x+y\addright{\frac{1}{3}x}\amp=-1\addright{\frac{1}{3}x}</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=-1+\frac{1}{3}x</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We can now substitute <m>-1+\frac{1}{3}x</m> for <m>y</m> in the first equation.  Before doing that, let's clear away the fractions from the first equation by multiplying both sides of the equation by the LCD of all of the fractions in the equation which is <m>4</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\frac{3}{4}x-\frac{5}{2}y\amp=\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{4}(\frac{3}{4}x-\frac{5}{2}y)\amp=\multiplyleft{4}\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                      <mrow>3x-10y\amp=7</mrow>
                      <mrow>3x-10(\substitute{-1+\frac{1}{3}x})\amp=7</mrow>
                      <mrow>3x+10-\frac{10}{3}x\amp=7</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Before proceeding any further, let's clear away the fraction by multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>3</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}(3x+10-\frac{10}{3}x)\amp=\multiplyleft{3}7</mrow>
                      <mrow>9x+30-10x\amp=21</mrow>
                      <mrow>-x+30\amp=21</mrow>
                      <mrow>-x+30\subtractright{30}\amp=21\subtractright{30}</mrow>
                      <mrow>-x\amp=-9</mrow>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{-1}-x\amp=\multiplyleft{-1}-9</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=9</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We can now determine the value for <m>y</m> after replacing <m>x</m> with <m>9</m> in the equation <m>y=-1+\frac{1}{3}x</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>y\amp=-1+\frac{1}{3} \cdot \substitute{9}</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=-1+3</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The solution to the given system of equations is the ordered pair <m>(9,2)</m>.  The solution is verified below.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          \frac{3}{4}\multiplyright{9}-\frac{5}{2}\multiplyright{2}\amp=\frac{7}{4}\,?\\
                          -\frac{1}{3}\multiplyright{9}+\substitute{2}\amp=-1\,?\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>

                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          \frac{27}{4}-5\amp=\frac{7}{4}\,?\\
                          -3+2\amp=-1\,\checkmark\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>

                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          \frac{27}{4}-\frac{20}{4}\amp=\frac{7}{4}\,\checkmark\\
                          -1\amp=-1\,\checkmark\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    We finish this workout by solving the following system of equations.
                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          -4x+7y\amp=-13\\
                          6x+14y\amp=9\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>
                    No avoiding fractions, but at least we can work with quarters.  Let's solve the first equation for <m>x</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>-4x+7y\amp=-13</mrow>
                      <mrow>-4x+7y\subtractright{7y}\amp=-13\subtractright{7y}</mrow>
                      <mrow>-4x\amp=-13-7y</mrow>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{4}}(-4x)\amp=\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{4}}(-13-7y)</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=\frac{13}{4}+\frac{7}{4}y</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Breath ... let's substitute <m>\frac{13}{4}+\frac{7}{4}y</m> for <m>x</m> in the second given equation.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>6\substitute{x}+14y\amp=9</mrow>
                      <mrow>6(\substitute{\frac{13}{4}+\frac{7}{4}y})+14y\amp=9</mrow>
                      <mrow>\frac{39}{2}+\frac{21}{2}y+14y\amp=9</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Let's clear away the fractions by multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>2</m> and then solve for <m>y</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}(\frac{39}{2}+\frac{21}{2}y+14y)\amp=\multiplyleft{2}9</mrow>
                      <mrow>39+21y+28y\amp=18</mrow>
                      <mrow>49y+39\amp=18</mrow>
                      <mrow>49y+39\subtractright{39}\amp=18\subtractright{39}</mrow>
                      <mrow>49y\amp=-21</mrow>
                      <mrow>\divideunder{49y}{49}\amp=\divideunder{-21}{49}</mrow>
                      <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{7}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Oh my.  Exhale.  Let's carry on.  Replacing <m>y</m> with <m>-\frac{3}{7}</m> in the equation <m>x=\frac{13}{4}+\frac{7}{4}y</m> will led to the value of <m>x</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>x\amp=\frac{13}{4}+\frac{7}{4}\multiplyright{-\frac{3}{7}}</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=\frac{13}{4}-\frac{3}{4}</mrow>
                      <mrow>x\amp=\frac{5}{2}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Alrighty, then.  The solution to the given system is the ordered pair <m>(\frac{5}{2},-\frac{3}{7})</m>.  This unlikely outcome is verified below.

                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          -4\multiplyright{\frac{5}{2}}+7\multiplyright{-\frac{3}{7}}\amp=-13\,?\\
                          6\multiplyright{\frac{5}{2}}+14\multiplyright{-\frac{3}{7}}\amp=9\,?\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>

                    <me>
                      \left\{
                        \begin{aligned}
                          -10-3\amp=-13\,\checkmark\\
                          15-6\amp=9\,\checkmark\\
                        \end{aligned}
                      \right.
                    </me>

                    Crikey.
                  </p>
                </li>

              </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

